  "body": " A diver leaps from a 3 meter springboard. His feet leave the board at time , he reaches his maximum height of 4.5 m at seconds, and enters the water at . Once in the water, the diver coasts to the bottom of the pool (depth 3.5 m), touches bottom at , rests for one second, and then pushes off the bottom. From there he coasts to the surface, and takes his first breath at .     Let denote the function that gives the height of the diver's feet (in meters) above the water at time . (Note that the height of the bottom of the pool is meters.) Sketch a carefully labeled graph of on the provided axes in Figure . Include scale and units on the vertical axis. Be as detailed as possible.    Axes for plotting in part (a).     Axes for plotting in part (c).       Based on your graph in (a), what is the average velocity of the diver between and ? Is his average velocity the same on every time interval within ?    Let the function represent the instantaneous vertical velocity of the diver at time (i.e. the speed at which the height function is changing; note that velocity in the upward direction is positive, while the velocity of a falling object is negative). Based on your understanding of the diver's behavior, as well as your graph of the position function, sketch a carefully labeled graph of on the axes provided in Figure . Include scale and units on the vertical axis. Write several sentences that explain how you constructed your graph, discussing when you expect to be zero, positive, negative, relatively large, and relatively small.    Is there a connection between the two graphs that you can describe? What can you say about the velocity graph when the height function is increasing? decreasing? Make as many observations as you can.         Sketch a plot where the diver's height at time is on the vertical axis. For instance, .      m\/sec. The average velocity is not the same on every time interval within .    When the diver is going upward, her velocity is positive. When she is going downward, her velocity is negative. At the peak of her dive and when her feet touch the bottom of the pool.     It looks like when the position function is steep, the velocity function's value is farther away from zero, and that whenever the height\/position function is rising\/increasing, the velocity function has a positive value. Similarly, whenever the position function is decreasing, the velocity is negative.         Taking into account the given information and our intuition about the diver's velocity, ketch a plot where the diver's height at time is on the vertical axis. For instance, .     First, we see that m\/sec. The average velocity is not the same on every time interval within , since the position function is not linear. Physically, we expect the water to make the diver's velocity change as she glides through the water.    When the diver is going upward, her velocity is positive. When she is going downward, her velocity is negative. At the peak of her dive and when her feet touch the bottom of the pool, her velocity is zero because the velocity is changing sign there. Sketch a possible graph accordingly.     It looks like when the position function is steep, the velocity function's value is farther away from zero, and that whenever the height\/position function is rising\/increasing, the velocity function has a positive value. Similarly, whenever the position function is decreasing, the velocity is negative.     "
