  "body": " The rate at which water flows through Table Rock Dam on the White River in Branson, MO, is measured in cubic feet per second (CFS). As engineers open the floodgates, flow rates are recorded according to the following chart.   Water flow data.    seconds,           flow in CFS,               What definite integral measures the total volume of water to flow through the dam in the 60 second time period provided by the table above?    Use the given data to calculate for the largest possible value of to approximate the integral you stated in (a). Do you think over- or under-estimates the exact value of the integral? Why?    Approximate the integral stated in (a) by calculating for the largest possible value of , based on the given data.    Compute and . What quantity do both of these values estimate? Which is a more accurate approximation?          .     .     .     ; . each estimates the average rate at which water flows through the dam on , and the first is more accurate.         Because is measured in cubic feet per second and is measured in seconds, the definite integral measures the total amount of water (in cubic feet) that flow through the dam in 60 seconds.    With function values and thus subintervals as the maximum number of intervals we can use, we can compute since we need to use every other data point to evaluate the function. Doing so, . Thus, approximately cubic feet of water pass through the dam on the interval .  We observe that appears to be increasing at an increasing rate on . In particular, the data suggests that is concave up on the interval. As such, the trapezoid rule will over-estimate the true value of the definite integral and the midpoint rule will under-estimate the value. Thus, .    In order to estimate the integral using , we need to know the value of along with . To find , we compute and . First . Similarly, . Thus, . Finally, we now have the information needed to compute . We thus find that .    First, . This is one estimate for the average value of on since , and . Thus, on average, water is flowing through the dam at a rate of cubic feet per second.  Next, is the average of the known values of on the interval , and thus is one estimate of the average value of . This average treats all of them equally, as opposed to which counts midpoints more than endpoints and is developed in such a way to remove some of the error inherent in using simple estimates like and . This simple average of rate values is analogous to using a left or right Riemann sum, and thus we expect that the estimate of the average value of that comes from is more accurate for computing the average rate at which water flows through the dam.     "
