  "body": " Suppose you play a game with a friend that involves rolling a standard six-sided die. Before a player can participate in the game, he or she must roll a six with the die. Assume that you roll first and that you and your friend take alternate rolls. In this exercise we will determine the probability that you roll the first six.     Explain why the probability of rolling a six on any single roll (including your first turn) is .    If you don't roll a six on your first turn, then in order for you to roll the first six on your second turn, both you and your friend had to fail to roll a six on your first turns, and then you had to succeed in rolling a six on your second turn. Explain why the probability of this event is .    Now suppose you fail to roll the first six on your second turn. Explain why the probability is that you to roll the first six on your third turn.    The probability of you rolling the first six is the probability that you roll the first six on your first turn plus the probability that you roll the first six on your second turn plus the probability that your roll the first six on your third turn, and so on. Explain why this probability is . Find the sum of this series and determine the probability that you roll the first six.         There are equally possible outcomes when we roll one die.    The three rolls are independent so the probability of the overall outcome is the product of the three probabilities.    See (b).     .         There are equally possible outcomes when we roll one die, and only one of those is a , so the probability that a appears when we roll the die is .    On the first roll, the probability of not rolling a is . This is the same on the second roll, so the probability of not rolling a on either of the first two rolls is , since the two events are independent. If we then roll a on the following turn, the probability of doing so in that roll is , so with the three rolls being independent, the probability of you rolling a on your second turn (the third overall roll) is .    The exact same reasoning as in (b), but with dice rolls instead of , shows that .    By simply summing the probabilities to consider all of the possible outcomes (rolling on your first turn, doing so on your second, etc.), we get that the total probability of you rolling a on one of your turns is , which is a geometric series with and . Since we know that a geometric series has sum , it follows that , so by going first your odds are just slightly better than half that you'll be the first one to roll a .     "
