  "body": " Conditionally convergent series exhibit interesting and unexpected behavior. In this exercise we examine the conditionally convergent alternating harmonic series and discover that addition is not commutative for conditionally convergent series. We will also encounter Riemann's Theorem concerning rearrangements of conditionally convergent series. Before we begin, we remind ourselves that , a fact which will be verified in a later section.     First we make a quick analysis of the positive and negative terms of the alternating harmonic series.     Show that the series diverges.    Show that the series diverges.    Based on the results of the previous parts of this exercise, what can we say about the sums and for any positive integer ? Be specific in your explanation.       Recall addition of real numbers is commutative; that is for any real numbers and . This property is valid for any sum of finitely many terms, but does this property extend when we add infinitely many terms together?  The answer is no, and something even more odd happens. Riemann's Theorem (after the nineteenth-century mathematician Georg Friedrich Bernhard Riemann) states that a conditionally convergent series can be rearranged to converge to any prescribed sum. More specifically, this means that if we choose any real number , we can rearrange the terms of the alternating harmonic series so that the sum is . To understand how Riemann's Theorem works, let's assume for the moment that the number we want our rearrangement to converge to is positive. Our job is to find a way to order the sum of terms of the alternating harmonic series to converge to .     Explain how we know that, regardless of the value of , we can find a partial sum  of the positive terms of the alternating harmonic series that equals or exceeds . Let .    Explain how we know that, regardless of the value of , we can find a partial sum  so that .    Explain how we know that, regardless of the value of , we can find a partial sum  of the remaining positive terms of the alternating harmonic series so that .    Explain how we know that, regardless of the value of , we can find a partial sum of the remaining negative terms of the alternating harmonic series so that .    Explain why we can continue this process indefinitely and find a sequence whose terms are partial sums of a rearrangement of the terms in the alternating harmonic series so that .        "
